<div id="review_2838208316" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2838208316" />
    <a title="reeder (reviews)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/86180240-reeder-reviews"><img alt="reeder (reviews)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535843169p2/86180240.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2838208316?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="reeder (reviews)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="reeder (reviews)" href="/user/show/86180240-reeder-reviews">reeder (reviews)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook " href="/book/show/29552812-the-scarlet-thread">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">agnostics who enjoy angst and imploding OW</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/86180240-reeder-reviews?shelf=cheaters-contrition-tour">cheaters-contrition-tour</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2838208316" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11055028336675394634">This is currently my third-favorite <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[cheating spouse <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> romance. But it only achieves bronze medal status because I&apos;m basically carving out my own version of this book by ignoring a couple of major dislikes. <br/><br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[<b>What works <i>really</i> well.</b> <br/>• Solid marital angst. <br/>The heroine suffers a lot of insults and emotional injury, such as the scene in which her husband insists on hiring a swank interior decorator for their new house because &quot;I don&apos;t want it looking like it</span></span>
  <span id="freeText11055028336675394634" style="display:none">This is currently my third-favorite <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[cheating spouse <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> romance. But it only achieves bronze medal status because I'm basically carving out my own version of this book by ignoring a couple of major dislikes. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<b>What works <i>really</i> well.</b> <br />• Solid marital angst. <br />The heroine suffers a lot of insults and emotional injury, such as the scene in which her husband insists on hiring a swank interior decorator for their new house because "I don't want it looking like it was decorated by someone running a flea market." As if he doesn't remember that his wife is the one who decorated their previous homes and he is therefore insulting her to her face. (Oh, and guess when they break up? JUST GUESS. I'll give you a hint: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[her mother is dying of cancer, so the wife goes back home to care for her for two weeks. When the kids arrive for their grandmother's funeral, they reveal that the nanny the heroine hired had to stay overnight four times because daddy was out working all night <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.) Really. Brutal. Angst.<br /><br />• The husband's motivation. <br />I love the consistent pattern here. Everything he does -- probably from the time he started dating the heroine fourteen years earlier, but definitely from the decision to move from Northern California to L.A. -- stems from his need to compensate for being the son of a Mexican immigrant. He's ambitious for all the markers of success, to be <u>better than</u> but <u>accepted by</u> the WASPy establishment. Those markers include a college degree with honors, a high-profile career with long hours, fancy cars, an expensive home, and -- eventually -- trading in his merely adequate middle-class, white, Protestant wife for the younger, blonde, Wellesley-educated East coast debutante who happens to work as his new firm's merchandising director. The trophiest of trophy wives.<br /><br />• The third-person limited POV<br />Although the narration is from the heroine's perspective, Rivers does an impressive job conveying the progress of the husband's affair to the reader before the heroine knows (or acknowledges) what's going on. <br /> <br /><b>I can take it or leave it</b><br />• Most of the religious stuff.<br />I was raised a Christian, and I'm comfortable with the belief system. What can make me uncomfortable when reading Christian/inspirational titles is fundamentalism, evangelicalism, or overt proselytizing (between the characters. I get that the author is proselytizing through the book to the reader). This heroine comes from a Christian background, so her Road to Damascus experience (literally on a road in L.A.) is, I suppose, akin to being born again. But, basically, I'm not thinking about religion too much EXCEPT when she and her cheater reunite and she's looking for the glue that will hold them together (because she has come to realize how very different they are). She decides Jesus is their common ground: "He brought us together, and He'll hold us together if we make Him our foundation...if we make drawing closer to Jesus our goal in life, how can we not draw closer to one another at the same time?" <br /><br />My concern here is that she's Protestant and he's Catholic, and she has already expressed that she doesn't want their two children's relationship to God to be mediated by a priest or "bound by guilt or penitence." On the other hand, the remorseful cheating husband could only find peace with his actions by going to confession. So...I'm not at all sure they have the same view of how to draw closer to Jesus and therefore each other. Focusing on this kind of compromises the HEA.<br /><br /><b>Some elements, I just kick to the curb.</b><br />• The entire "parallel" story of her quilt-sewing ancestor who was dragged west by her husband and who, in the process of suffering many trials, came to love God. It wasn't particularly well-integrated and honestly didn't seem to add to my understanding of the main storyline. I started skimming, then skipping entirely. Fortunately, in the ebook version these sections are formatted completely differently, so skipping was easy.<br /><br />• The blame the wife assumes for her husband's affair. <br />No. Just no. True, the wife isn't perfect in the marriage, and the book is stronger for it. Prior to their move, when the husband tried to discuss his career goals, she passive-aggressively avoided engaging with the topic and therefore acts stunned when he announces he has taken a new job in L.A. She doesn't want to move away from her home and extended family in Healdsburg, so she's sullen about it and makes little attempt to adjust to their new home. She's hostile about his long work hours and refuses to praise his accomplishments. <br /><br />Reflecting on the progression of her husband's affair, the heroine theorizes:<br /><blockquote><b>They'd started having lunch together, then dinner. A few drinks led to more. Then the guilt set in, and the only way to alleviate that was to cast blame. Sierra knew she'd become the perfect target. She had already set herself up for the fall by her own childish behavior months before Elizabeth Longford ever came on the scene. If it hadn't been Elizabeth, it would have been another woman.</b></blockquote> This I mostly agree with. Nevertheless, her "childish behavior" wasn't the cause of the affair. Even if Sierra had been the perfect doormat wife, her husband still would have been attracted by everything the OW represented and still would have felt guilty and still would have blamed his wife to justify his infidelity, but in this "good wife" scenario, he would have blamed Sierra for not being accomplished enough, educated enough, classy enough. <br /><br />So she can blame herself for making the affair easier and more appealing because of her behavior, but the choice to have an affair was his alone. Well, his and the OW's. Which is why I go ballistic when the heroine assumes responsibility for causing the OW pain:<br /><br /><blockquote><b>"It's like a chain reaction. I was so angry with you when we moved down here. I never listened to what you wanted or needed. I was only interested in what I wanted. I hurt you so much, and out of that I hurt Elizabeth, too."<br />...<br />"If I'd been the wife I should've been, you never would've turned to her. So I share the blame with you for her pain, too."</b></blockquote><br /><br />No, really, you do not. Your husband dumped the OW because she turned out to be a bigot, which is a huge problem for him. So her ultimate pain is the result of her own bad behavior. Even if your husband had left her solely because he wanted to return to you, Elizabeth's bad behavior in pursuing a relationship with a married man would have been the cause of her pain. Elizabeth is pretty much responsible for Elizabeth here.<br /><br />So a four-star cheating book loses a star because even though I can pretend this conversation never happened, I can't expect others to ignore the heroine's gratuitous remorse.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="11055028336675394634" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


