    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2590070758" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2590070758" />
    <a title="Samira Kanetkar" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51600385-samira-kanetkar"><img alt="Samira Kanetkar" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609529207p2/51600385.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2590070758?book_show_action=true">Dec 04, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Samira Kanetkar" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Samira Kanetkar" href="/user/show/51600385-samira-kanetkar">Samira Kanetkar</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2590070758&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2590070758" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5954997361631738636">This book frustrated me to no end and I’m honestly surprised I finished it with how much it had me seething. <br/><br/>Maybe it’s the feminist in me, but I absolutely could not stand this book’s portrayal of marriage and gender roles. The main character’s sole identity is rooted in being a wife to Alex and mother to his children. Sierra didn’t go to college or get a job. She has no passions or friends. She just submissively accepts that her life will be dedicated to supporting her husband through all his </span>
  <span id="freeText5954997361631738636" style="display:none">This book frustrated me to no end and I’m honestly surprised I finished it with how much it had me seething. <br /><br />Maybe it’s the feminist in me, but I absolutely could not stand this book’s portrayal of marriage and gender roles. The main character’s sole identity is rooted in being a wife to Alex and mother to his children. Sierra didn’t go to college or get a job. She has no passions or friends. She just submissively accepts that her life will be dedicated to supporting her husband through all his endeavors and raising his children. Things appear to be going fine until Alex gets a promotion and ACCEPTS IT WITHOUT CONFRONTING HER. Yes, you read that correctly. Her husband accepts a job offer in a different city without consulting his wife. Then, when she expresses discontent (as any woman who is about to uproot her family would) he becomes defensive and accuses her of not supporting his dreams. She reluctantly goes and is obviously upset by the move, and he does nothing to console her. He becomes increasingly work-obsessed, which has an immense toll of their relationship. He begins to berate her and blame her for every little thing that goes wrong and attributes their failing marriage to her supposed shortcomings instead of his own. He is petulant, vindictive, and severely neglects his children. He very predictably leaves her for a younger woman he knows from work. <br /><br />As if all this horrible behavior wasn’t enough, my dislike for Alex was confirmed when her mother is diagnosed with cancer. Although they are separated at this point, he completely turns his back on the mother-in-law he was once so close to. Despite the turmoil in his marriage, he still could have reached out before she finally dies, especially considering the mother supported his move and encouraged her daughter to give it a chance. To turn your back on someone as they deal with the grief and loss of losing their last remaining parent is a kind of cruel that is unforgivable. <br /><br />While I do agree that Sierra grows immensely (by finally getting a job, supporting her children on her own, and getting along fine without her cheating husband) it KILLED ME when she finds her faith and then proceeds to shoulder almost all the blame for her failed marriage. She literally tells her husband if she had “been a better wife” that he would not have turned to another woman. This shocked me. I’m all for forgiving and trying to make amends but to excuse your husband’s behavior like that? It suggests that men have no control over their actions and should not be held accountable. It makes his cheating seem inevitable and entirely her own fault, not his. Even if you weren’t being the best wife, it doesn’t give your husband permission to have an affair. Sierra is entirely too forgiving. <br /><br />Not so shockingly, they get back together and not by truly working through what happened. Instead, their reconciliation is sparked by a mutual belief in God. As if the reason their marriage deteriorated wasn’t because her husband changed drastically and left his family for another woman, but because God was not at the center of their relationship. They both come to a consensus that his cheating, her mother’s death, and every hardship they encountered was destined to occur and was a part of God’s plan to reunite them. I had a really hard time believing that their marriage was salvaged by a religious epiphany (especially when Sierra acts joyously shocked when Alex says he’s believed in God his whole life. How were y’all married fifteen years and never discussed religion?) <br /><br />Overall, this book left me incredibly disappointed, not just with its excessive preachiness at the end (which is to be expected given this is a Francine Rivers novel) but with its unrealistic portrayal of a communication-less, misogynistic marriage that is saved at the hands of God.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5954997361631738636" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


